Maybe a fisheye lens for a nest box is a bit too much.
You learn something new every day.
I should have known better since I built one with a "normal" lens before.
I'll write more about it over the weekend once I've installed the second one.
Let's just say that the birds will have better internet access than I did in 2015.
Zumindest ist das der Plan.
Der Kasten, in dem schon ein Nest ist, saugt viel WLAN-Daten.
Beim anderen wirds etwas schwieriger, dass er online gehen kann.
Okay, ich hab heute den neuen Nistkasten aufgehängt. So sieht er an seinem neuen Platz im Garten aus.
Aber gehen wir etwas zurück. Niemand fragt: „Was genau ist da drin?“
On top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera and a fisheye lens, and an IR LED that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swivel side wall of the birdhouse. I bought it like this and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there's no power in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 battery.
I didn't photograph the battery or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse is the battery.
If it's charged, I have about 4 hours of runtime.
Now, that's what I call a feature. This way, the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last autumn in the fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
This is almost a shame because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and direct it downwards into the garden.
Maybe I'll do that when/if I set up more cameras for birdhouses. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably will need it.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It turned itself off only an hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery stopped charging three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or maybe less than half a day wasn't enough to fully charge the battery.
I'll have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I have no telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
Generally, a few more sensors would be a good idea, I think.
And perhaps a battery that at least theoretically is capable of keeping the system running overnight.
Oh right, and another objective.
Fisheye is quite excessive.
But I am already looking for parts at Digikey, so I can build my own board specifically for this.
Or not. We will see.
And he is still offline.
Nice.
According to the actual solar cells on the house, we have only about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Wait another one or two hours to see what happens – or doesn't happen.
Still offline.
It's never easy anyway.
I realized that the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger had 5V and GND swapped on the silkscreen.
I switched the cables and now the charge indicator is lighting up.
The ESP did not immediately go online. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and it is still offline.
It looks like it is rebooting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think this panel is simply not working. I have now ordered a larger one and hope that will work.
Take a look at what I found in my workshop.
A 24V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partly behind a tree) that the value practically drops to zero as soon as I start the device.
Probably I'll have to wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this setup or if I need the better panel that I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought this panel in 2021 and it should deliver 12V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or my multimeter, or the data has been changed.
Good news!
Sie haben die Daten geändert und die, die ich habe, sind falsch.
Der alte und auch der neue Listing-Titel nennen es ein 12 V 10-W-Panel.
Deshalb lösche ich nie alte E-Mails.
Oh schaut! Das Ding ging vor ungefähr einer Stunde, für etwa eine halbe Minute wieder online.
Vielleicht hat das Panel die Batterie gerade lange genug für 38 Sekunden Laufzeit aufgeladen. Dafür hat es nur etwas mehr als zwei Stunden gebraucht.
Ratet mal: Today it's cloudy. I'm not sure if the (probably broken) solar panel will generate enough power.
Let's wait and see.
Update: I installed the new panel and now it seems to be working.
It could still go offline as soon as the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
Fun fact: I use the Ping integration in Home Assistant to check if it's online or not.
The average connection time is 102 ms. Not particularly good, but also not terribly bad.
